<span style="font-size: 10px;">The Apollo landing on the Moon, the Space Shuttle, and space activity in general most likely conjure images of scientific endeavor and symbols of human achievement. This Note advocates legal change to promote commercial space activity; however, not for intellectual value alone. Space industrialization and commercialization offer immeasurable economic and humanitarian rewards unrealized by the average person or lawyer. The space industry is already a multi-billion dollar industry. It is also an industry in which the United States does not necessarily lead. The European Space Agency captures the majority of commercial launch contracts, affecting not only the commercial launch industry, but the satellite, remote sensing, and all other related enterprises. Third-world countries are also major competitors in the space industry. </span>
